\section*{Exercise 1}

R comes along with a lot of sample datasets. A very popular one is called \texttt{iris}, which holds sepal and petal measurements for different iris sub-species. The dataset is directly available to you by the variable name \texttt{iris}.

\begin{itemize}
	\item Look at the first and last few observations in the dataframe to get a first idea about the structure of the data.
	\item Calculate summary statistics for each of the columns.
	\item Calculate summary statistics for each of the sub-species separately.\\
	(\textit{Hint: You can use double brackets to extract an element from a list: \texttt{list\_with\_data[[1]]} returns the first element of the list.})
	\item You can plot each column combination of a dataframe by using the \texttt{plot} function. Do this. What do you see? Can you identify patterns?
\end{itemize}


